- It's closer to the viewer than a line behind<br>
- It sets an object off from the background<br>
- it's on the side of an object that's away from a light source (ie, where shadows will be cast).<br>
<br>
The tutorial you were just pointed to is very good.  If you don't like going over things several times, there are a few options.<br>
<br>
- Brushes will give tons of line-width variation.  They have a different look than pens so using brushes and pens together will take practice.  Use a good one and practice a lot.  Practice basic strokes on separate sheets of paper.  Especially practice evenly tapering the line or maintaining the same weight for a long line.<br>
<br>
- For a more &quot;manga&quot; look, use a dip pen.  Favourites of artists in Japan are G-pens.  My personal favourite is a Hunt 108, which acts similar but I find it easier to use.  Pressing a little harder will give you width, while lightening up will give a nice fine line.  There are also pens that will give even lines, heavy or light.<br>
<br>
- If you still want to use a technical pen, use several.  Use a 005 for fine details, a 01 for medium details, a 03 for the main drawing, and a 05 for thicker lines... just to start.  You can get a lot out of those pens.  If you don't mind destroying your pens a little more quickly, a 005 or 01 can get more variation if you push down on them a bit.<br>
